article.headline: Despite big lead, K-State works to put Mizzou away
article.linkText: Fifth-ranked K-State holds off resilient Missouri
article.story:
COLUMBIA, Mo. (AP) -- Even with a huge lead, Kansas State didn't
feel comfortable against Missouri.

	   Megan Mahoney scored 21 points and Kendra Wecker added 18 as No.
5 Kansas State held off a late rally to beat Missouri 66-56
Wednesday night. Mahoney also had 12 rebounds for her fourth
double-double of the season. Nicole Ohlde scored 17 points and
added 11 rebounds for the Wildcats, her league-leading 11th
double-double of the season.

	   Wecker, the Big 12's leading scorer, made six of 18 shots. She
scored in double digits for the 39th straight game.

	   After being down by as many as 20 early in the second half,
Missouri (13-10, 7-5 Big 12) used an 8-0 run to cut the lead to
51-43 with 7:36 left. Reserves Angie Carter and Cherice Mack scored
six of those points for Missouri.

	   The Tigers held Kansas State without a field goal for 7:14 until
Ohlde scored with 2:30 left to put the Wildcats up 58-51.

	   ``We had some defensive breakdowns,'' Mahoney said. ``But I
think that's something we just kind of had to fight through. We
built ourselves a lead, but they were tough. They weren't going to
give up.''

	   Missouri got as close as 56-51 with 2:53 left, but late missed
shots cost the Tigers.

	   ``Especially in this league, teams aren't going to lie down,''
Kansas State coach Deb Patterson said. ``I thought Missouri took
their intensity and their focus to another level. It was, 'We've
got nothing to lose, let's play with some pride and intensity.' I
felt they really picked it up.''

	   Kansas State (24-2, 11-1) won its sixth straight and has won 19
of its last 20. The Wildcats, who used only six players and got all
of their scoring from the starting five, also tied the series
between the schools at 31.

	   Kerensa Barr led Missouri with 17 points and Evan Unrau added
15.

	   Kansas State, which entered the game as the league's top
shooting team at 48.8 percent, made 44 percent. The Wildcats also
entered the game outscoring Big 12 opponents by an average of 21.8
points per game.

	   Kansas State capitalized on poor Missouri shooting early. The
Wildcats made nine of their first 14 shots to take a 21-8 lead.
Despite making just two of their next 14 during the next 10
minutes, Kansas State had a 34-17 advantage at halftime. The Tigers
made eight of 28 shots in the half.

	   Mahoney, who had 10 points in the game's first eight minutes,
led all scorers in the first half with 13 points on 5-for-8
shooting.

	   ``She's kind of the unsung hero of that team,'' Missouri coach
Cindy Stein said. ``She's kind of the engine that makes that team
go.''

	   Missouri missed all eight of its 3-point attempts in the first
half, while Kansas State was 5-of-9. Despite shooting 38 percent in
the first half, the Wildcats outrebounded Missouri 24-17.
